An alternative way to do distributed training using context manager (#238)

* RegressionBlock: c_out --> n_out

* An alternative way to do distributed training using context manager.  Synopsis:  `with learn.distrib_ctx(gpu): learn.fit(....)`

Usage: see the simplification in train_imagenette.py.

- Localize the use of distributed GPU to only when needed, auto-cleanup DistributedTrainer/DistributedDL afterwards, thus avoid these two from interfering with other learner operations after the `fit()`, such as with `show_results()`.

- On-demand distributed training means `LRFinder` should work as-is, without using distributed data parallel mode, and yet later the same learner object can be trained distributedly.

- Optionally can create destory a torch distributed_process_group within the context on the fly, if the caller didn't create one.

-  Simplify the usage, by refactoring the call to `setup_distrib(gpu)`, and the conditionalized call to use of `if num_distrib() > 1: learner.to_distributed()`, down to a `with learn.distrib_ctx(gpu):` context clause.

F.interpolate compatability patch for pytorch 1.5.0 (#400)

* Add recompute_scale_factor=True to RatioResize

F.interpolate, used by the RatioResize transform in fastai2’s batch image augmenter, changed it’s default behaviour between pytorch versions v1.4.0 and v1.5.0, causing installations using pytorch v1.5.0 (such as google colab) to throw a warning that using F.interpolate in this way will fail in future. Adding the argument “recompute_scale_factor=True” when calling F.interpolate prevents pytorch from throwing this warning, and ensures fastai compatibility with future versions of pytorch.

* Add recompute_scale_factor=True to RatioResize

* Update 09_vision.augment.ipynb

* Add recompute_scale_factor=True to RatioResize on pytorch > v1.4.0

F.interpolate, used by the RatioResize transform in fastai2’s batch image augmenter, will change default behaviour in pytorch v1.6.0, causing installations using pytorch v1.5.0 (such as google colab) to throw a warning. Selectively adding the argument “recompute_scale_factor=True” when calling F.interpolate on pytorch > v.1.4.x prevents pytorch from throwing this warning, and ensures fastai2 compatibility with future versions of pytorch.

* Add recompute_scale_factor=True to RatioResize on pytorch > v1.4.0

Selectively adding the argument “recompute_scale_factor=True” when calling F.interpolate on pytorch > v.1.4.x prevents pytorch from throwing this warning, and ensures fastai2 compatibility with future versions of pytorch.

* Add recompute_scale_factor=True to RatioResize if pytorch > v1.4.0

nn.functional.interpolate, used by the RatioResize transform in fastai2’s batch image augmenter, will change default behaviour in pytorch v1.6.0, causing installations using pytorch v1.5.0 (such as google colab) to throw a warning. Selectively adding the argument “recompute_scale_factor=True” when calling F.interpolate on pytorch > v.1.4.x prevents pytorch from throwing this warning, and ensures fastai2 compatibility with future versions of pytorch.
